173 (c) Any unclassified employee who is employed by the
174 commission on the effective date of this act and was appointed
175 by a commissioner shall continue to be employed without regard
176 to his or her appointing authority. The Secretary of Energy
177 shall, in consultation with the State Personnel Board, work to
178 transfer these unclassified employees into classified
179 service."
180 Section 3. Sections 37-1-81.1 and 31-1-81.2 are added
181 to the Code of Alabama 1975 to read as follows:
182 §37-1-81.1
183 (a) The retail base rates established and in place on
184 October 1, 2026 for each utility that is regulated by the
185 commission and that provides retail electric service may not
186 be increased before January 1, 2029.
187 (b) On and after January 1, 2029, a utility that
188 provides retail electric service may not factor the following
189 costs into the calculation or determination of a new rate or
190 service regulation or a change to an existing rate or service
191 regulation charged to customers of the utility:
192 (1) Costs incurred due to the utility providing funding
193 or grants that impact rates to other persons or organizations.
194 (2) Costs incurred due to the hiring of persons for the
195 purpose of lobbying the Legislature or any other political
196 office or subdivision of the state.
Page 7

office or subdivision of the state.
SB360 Engrossed
197 (3) Costs incurred due to advertisement of the utility
198 other than public safety advertising approved by the
199 commission.
200 (c)(1) When an electric utility files a new schedule to
201 put in operation a new rate or service regulation or to change
202 an existing rate or service regulation, the utility shall
203 affirm that the utility has not included the prohibited costs
204 under subsection (b) in the calculation or determination of
205 the rate or service regulation.
206 (2) If the electric utility fails to make the
207 affirmation, the rate or service regulation shall be void.
208 (d) If the commission discovers that a utility has
209 included the prohibited cost under subsection (b) in the
210 calculation or determination of rates or service regulations,
211 the commission shall investigate the determination pursuant to
212 Section 37-1-83 and other powers of investigation granted to
213 the commission pursuant to this division.
214 §37-1-81.2
215 The commissioners and staff of the commission shall
216 convene at least one public meeting per calendar year with
217 utility representatives to provide information to the public
218 on cost trends, reliability, resilience, general
219 infrastructure investment plans, economic development impacts,
220 security of the power grid, national trends in energy
221 production, and other regulatory issues the Secretary of
222 Energy deems relevant. The public meetings shall be conducted
223 in a manner that gives residents the opportunity to
224 participate, addresses concerns voiced by the public, and
Page 8

participate, addresses concerns voiced by the public, and
SB360 Engrossed
225 provides a review of key issues that the secretary believes
226 will be helpful to the public in understanding issues that
227 impact services under its jurisdiction.
228 Section 4. Sections 17-14-2, 17-14-3, and 36-3-1, Code
229 of Alabama 1975, are amended to make conforming changes to
230 read as follows:
231 "§17-14-2
232 General elections throughout the state shall be held
233 for Governor, Lieutenant Governor, Attorney General, Auditor,
234 Secretary of State, Treasurer, Commissioner of Agriculture and
235 Industries, three public service commissioners, no two of whom
236 shall be elected from the same from each congressional
237 district, Chief Justice and associate justices of the Supreme
238 Court, judges of the courts of appeals, electors for President
239 and Vice President of the United States, United States
240 senators, and such other officers as may be required by law to
241 be elected by the voters of the entire state; for a member of
242 Congress in each congressional district; judges of the circuit
243 court in each judicial circuit; judges of the district courts
244 in each district; district attorneys in each judicial circuit;
245 a senator in each senatorial district; a representative in the
246 Legislature in each house district; a judge of the probate
247 court, sheriff, clerks of the circuit courts, tax assessor,
248 tax collector, a county treasurer in counties of more than
249 56,000 population, as provided by law, coroner, and members of
250 the county commission in each county, and constables in each
251 precinct of the county."
252 "§17-14-3
